{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ffb73bb9-b962-44ba-9c0b-27ecf85ce260","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Tests Losing History in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID algorithm**. The new IDs don't match the v3 IDs, so Azure DevOps treats every test as new. To restore history, add this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr, if you want the new IDs going forward, accept the one-time history break.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-scoped context** — there's no specific test running yet. Accessing `TestName` now throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it happened to return the first test's name, but that was unreliable and is now explicitly disallowed.\n\n**Fix for your code** — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`, or move that logic into `[TestInitialize]` where a per-test context exists:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // valid here\n}\n```\n\n## Other MSTest v4 Breaking Changes to Watch For\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallelization** | Tests run in parallel by default. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or `DoNotParallelize` if you relied on serial execution. |\n| **Timeout default** | Test method timeouts now use `CooperativeCancellation` by default (checks `CancellationToken` rather than aborting threads). |\n| **`[ClassCleanup]`** | Default timing changed to `EndOfClass` (was `EndOfAssembly` in v3). |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` for collections** | Improved type checking may surface previously-hidden type mismatches. |\n| **`DeploymentItem`** | Stricter validation; paths that silently failed in v3 may now error. |\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` and `TestProject.csproj` to fix the two issues you're hitting?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8fda2a3a-b8bb-414e-b498-5d91e99386ba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide what I know about these changes:\n\n1. **Test ID changes (tests losing history in Azure DevOps)**: In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation algorithm changed. MSTest v3 used a legacy ID format, while v4 uses a new stable ID format by default. This causes Azure DevOps (and other CI systems) to see them as entirely new tests because the IDs don't match the old ones. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` or use the `[TestId]` attribute or a specific MSBuild property to keep the legacy IDs.\n\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: Another significant change is that `TestContext.TestName` is no longer available in `[ClassInitialize]` methods — it throws an exception or returns null since class-level initialization runs once for the entire class rather than per individual test. MSTest v3 would return the first test's name, but v4 formalized this as invalid behavior.\n3. I should also cover other potential breaking changes to watch for.","outputTokens":971,"requestId":"4813:1B7094:65FEBF6:6E6E6C2:69FC0165"},"id":"0b3d9afa-b990-45f4-8067-b88d19cfb970","timestamp":"2026-05-07T03:05:31.766Z","parentId":"bf86da3c-1c10-4452-9a30-0e7620f67f95"}
